"1340":"1340","1390":"1390","1290":"1290","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","East Harling, Norfolk, England":"East Harling, Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bourn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (southeastern): variant of   Bourne  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bourne","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived beside a stream, from southern Middle English <i>bourne</i>, Old English <i>burna</i>, <i>burne</i> ‘spring, stream’, or a habitational name from a place called with this word, for example Bourn in Cambridgeshire or Bourne in Lincolnshire. In surnames the reference is often to an old stream called <i>burna</i>, surviving as the name of a farm. This word was replaced as the general word for a stream in southern dialects by Old English <i>brōc</i> (see   Brook  ) and came to be restricted in meaning to a stream flowing only intermittently, especially in winter."]}]},{"name":"Nicholas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Nicholas Bourn was born in 1290, in Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. She married Nicholas Bourn. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"1290–":"1290–Surnud","1290–1340":"1290–1340","1322–1390":"1322–1390","1290–Female":"1290–Surnud","1322":"1322","1340":"1340","1390":"1390","1290":"1290","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","East Harling, Norfolk, England":"East Harling, Norfolk, England"},"fi":{"1290–":"1290–Kuollut","1290–1340":"1290–1340","1322–1390":"1322–1390","1290–Female":"1290–Kuollut","1322":"1322","1340":"1340","1390":"1390","1290":"1290","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","East Harling, Norfolk, England":"East Harling, Norfolk, England"},"fr":{"1290–":"1290–Décédée","1290–1340":"1290–1340","1322–1390":"1322–1390","1290–Female":"1290–Décédée","1322":"1322","1340":"1340","1390":"1390","1290":"1290","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","East Harling, Norfolk, England":"East Harling, Norfolk, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Nicholas Bourn est née en 1290, à Suffolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a épousé Nicholas Bourn. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille. Elle est décédée dans sa ville natale."},"de":{"1290–":"1290–Verstorben","1290–1340":"1290–1340","1322–1390":"1322–1390","1290–Female":"1290–Verstorben","1322":"1322","1340":"1340","1390":"1390","1290":"1290","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","East Harling, Norfolk, England":"East Harling, Norfolk, England","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Nicholas Bourn wurde 1290 in Suffolk, England, United Kingdom geboren. Sie hat Nicholas Bourn geheiratet. Sie hatten mindestens 1 Tochter. Sie starb in ihrem Geburtsort."},"ht":{"1290–":"1290–Desede","1290–1340":"1290–1340","1322–1390":"1322–1390","1290–Female":"1290–Des